<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=96663226525873></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96663226525873><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=13&mid=96663226525873>Soloing Dual Spawns...</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=13&mid=96663226525873#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=1><span id=Administrator>Illia</span></a>, <span id=Administrator>Administrator</span><br><span id=notbold>156 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Aug 18th 4:57 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.62]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>There are a few places where only two and only two creatures spawn together in close succession.&nbsp;&nbsp;Enchanters tend to gravitate towards these spots, as they offer the ability to use our charm line of spells to solo.<br><br><b>Warning:</b>  The following tactic may or may not result in any net experience gain.  Despite it being rather xp heavy, it's also quite prone to quick deaths.<br><br>At level 34, my previous groups had taken a break, so I took the opportunity to learn how to solo for a while.  I had a nasty time at the start, but as time went on I picked up this tactic:<br><br>Starting in either the East or West commons, there are sets of Rangers who spawn in pairs.  In West commons this is just behind the druid ring.  In east commons there is an obilisk near the WC zone.  There are always two NPCs here, usually from a pot of about 6 total names which may appear.<br><br>These rangers are about level 30, they melee for about 70, and cast the standard ranger spells.  there is the odd druid who appears, who cast's slightly stronger spells.<br><br>They're on a 6 minute timer, and drop a maximum of 4pp plus the potential of a fine steel weapon and/or a longbow.  XP's pretty good (unless charm breaks early.<br><br>My tactic was to open with charm on the nearer, which would have both of the rangers running toward you.  (One as pet, one as enemy) <br><br>Backing up, while the spells recycle buys a bit of time.  The next spell would be root on my target.  I would rarely need to ever tell ym pet to attack as the ptarget would usually get a spell off on me before.<br><br>It's important to buff with everything (including rune) as the rangers do hit and cast hard.  In the event of an early break of charm, chances are you'll need a speed boosting spell or item in order to get away.<br><br>Since the pet has the ability top heal itself, I also tended to break my pet's charm spell quickly after the fight to conserve mana for the last kill.<br><br>Oh, faction hits for the rangers are:<br>Kithicor Residents - down.<br>Jagged Pine Treefolk - down.<br>Protectors of Pine - down<br>Unkempt preservers - up.<br><br>Hope that helps all ye Ranger killers out there..<br><br><br><br><br>&nbsp;<br>--Illia<br><span style='color: maroon;'><a href=HTTP://everquest.allakhazam.com/db/userinfo.html?char=2 target=_new>Illia's Gear</a></span style='color: maroon;'></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
